The confirmed death toll in the Papua New Guinea tsunami rose to 705, mostly children.
Eyewitnesses reported that nothing was left in the devastated area but coconut trees, with missionaries and villagers burying the dead where they lay on the beaches, while salt water crocodiles fed on corpses.
Australia continued to provide aid, sending water sanitation equipment.
They also used data from the tsunami in research into tsunamis that might affect them.
New Zealand joined the active relief effort sending medical supplies and medical team.
The Pope dedicated a service, Madeleine Albright offered $25,000, and France offered to help.
